    {
      "content": "Integrating Applications with Azure Active Directory",
      "pos": [
        518,
        570
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Enterprise developers and software-as-a-service (SaaS) providers can develop commercial cloud services or line of business applications that can be integrated with Azure Active Directory (Azure AD) to provide secure sign in and authorization for their services.",
      "pos": [
        571,
        832
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To integrate an application or service with Azure AD, a developer must first register the details about their application with Azure AD by using the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        833,
        1006
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This article shows you how to add, update, or remove an application in Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        1008,
        1088
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You will learn about the different types of applications that can be integrated with Azure AD, how to configure your applications to access other resources such as web APIs, and more.",
      "pos": [
        1089,
        1272
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1274,
        1607
      ],
      "content": "To more information about app properties, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Application Objects and Service Principal Objects<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-application-objects.md)</ept>; to learn the branding guidelines you should use when developing applications with Azure Active Directory, see <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Branding Guidelines for Integrated Apps<ept id=\"p2\">](active-directory-branding-guidelines.md)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Adding an Application",
      "pos": [
        1612,
        1633
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Any application that wants to use the capabilities of Azure AD must first be registered in a directory.",
      "pos": [
        1635,
        1738
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This registration process involves giving Azure AD details about your application, such as the URL where it’s located, the URL to send replies after a user is authenticated, the URI that identifies the app, and so on.",
      "pos": [
        1739,
        1956
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you’re building a web application that just needs sign-on for users in Azure AD, you can simply follow the instructions below.",
      "pos": [
        1958,
        2087
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your application needs access to a web API, you’re building a native application that needs to access a web API, or you want to make your application multi-tenant, you’ll need to continue reading in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Updating an Application<ept id=\"p1\">](#updating-an-application)</ept> section to continue configuring your application.",
      "pos": [
        2088,
        2395
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you want to make your application available to other organizations, you will also need to enable external access once the application has been added.",
      "pos": [
        2397,
        2549
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To register an application in the Azure Management Portal",
      "pos": [
        2555,
        2612
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign in to the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        2617,
        2656
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Click on the Active Directory icon on the left menu, and then click on the desired directory.",
      "pos": [
        2661,
        2754
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the top menu, click Applications.",
      "pos": [
        2759,
        2795
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If no apps have been added to your directory, this page will only show the Add an App link.",
      "pos": [
        2796,
        2887
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Click on the link, or alternatively you can click on the Add button on the command bar.",
      "pos": [
        2888,
        2975
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the What do you want to do page, click on the link to Add an application my organization is developing.",
      "pos": [
        2980,
        3086
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the Tell us about your application page, you must specify a name for your application as well as indicate the type of application you are registering with Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        3091,
        3258
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can choose from a web application and/or web API (default) or native client application which represents an application that is installed on a device such as a phone or computer.Once finished, click the arrow icon on the bottom-right corner of the page.",
      "pos": [
        3260,
        3517
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the App properties page, provide the Sign-on URL and App ID URI for your web application (or just the Redirect URI for a native client application), then click the checkbox in the bottom-right hand corner of the page.",
      "pos": [
        3522,
        3742
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your application has been added, and you will be taken to the Quick Start page for your application.",
      "pos": [
        3747,
        3847
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Depending on whether your application is a web or native application, you will see different options on how to add additional capabilities to your application.",
      "pos": [
        3848,
        4007
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once your application has been added, you can begin updating your application to enable users to sign in, access web APIs in other applications, or configure multi-tenant application (which allows other organizations to access your application).",
      "pos": [
        4008,
        4253
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4256,
        4404
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> By default, the newly created application registration is configured to allow users from your directory to sign in to your application."
    },
    {
      "content": "Updating an Application",
      "pos": [
        4409,
        4432
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once your application has been registered with Azure AD, it may need to be updated to provide access to web APIs, be made available in other organizations, and more.",
      "pos": [
        4434,
        4599
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This section describes how to configure your application further.",
      "pos": [
        4600,
        4665
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information on the way authentication works in Azure AD, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Authentication Scenarios for Azure AD<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-authentication-scenarios.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4666,
        4822
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Overview of the Consent Framework",
      "pos": [
        4828,
        4861
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure AD’s new consent framework makes it easy to develop web and native applications that need to access web APIs secured by Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        4863,
        4998
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These web APIs include the Graph API, Office 365, and other Microsoft services, in addition to your own web APIs.",
      "pos": [
        4999,
        5112
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The framework is based on a user or an administrator giving consent to an application to be registered in their directory, which may involve accessing directory data.",
      "pos": [
        5113,
        5279
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if a web application needs to call Office 365’s web API to read calendar information about the user, that user will be required to consent to the application.",
      "pos": [
        5280,
        5451
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After consent is given, the web application will be able to call the Office 365 web API on behalf of the user, and use the calendar information as needed.",
      "pos": [
        5452,
        5606
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The consent framework is built on OAuth 2.0 and its various flows, such as authorization code grant and client credentials grant, using public or confidential clients.",
      "pos": [
        5608,
        5775
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By using OAuth 2.0, Azure AD makes it possible to build many different types of client applications, such as on a phone, tablet, server, or a web application, and gain access to the required resources.",
      "pos": [
        5776,
        5977
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        5979,
        6369
      ],
      "content": "For more detailed information about the consent framework, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>OAuth 2.0 in Azure AD<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn645545.aspx)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Authentication Scenarios for Azure AD<ept id=\"p2\">](active-directory-authentication-scenarios.md)</ept>, and Office 365’s topic <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Authentication and Authorization using Common Consent Framework<ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/office/dn605895(v=office.15).aspx)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Example of the consent experience",
      "pos": [
        6376,
        6409
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following steps will show you how the consent experience works for both the application developer and user.",
      "pos": [
        6411,
        6522
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On your application’s configuration page in the Azure Management Portal, set the permissions your application requires by using the drop-down menus in the Permissions to other applications control.",
      "pos": [
        6527,
        6724
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Permissions to other applications",
      "pos": [
        6732,
        6765
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider that your application’s permissions have been updated, the application is running, and a user is about to use it for the first time.",
      "pos": [
        6838,
        6979
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the application has not already acquired an access or refresh token, the application needs to go to Azure AD’s authorization endpoint to obtain an authorization code that can be used to acquire a new access and refresh token.",
      "pos": [
        6980,
        7208
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the user is not already authenticated, they’ll be asked to sign in to Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        7213,
        7295
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "User or administrator sign in to Azure AD",
      "pos": [
        7303,
        7344
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the user has signed in, Azure AD will determine if the user needs to be shown a consent page.",
      "pos": [
        7421,
        7520
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This determination is based on whether the user (or their organization’s administrator) has already granted the application consent.",
      "pos": [
        7521,
        7653
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If consent has not already been granted, Azure AD will prompt the user for consent and will display the required permissions it needs to function.",
      "pos": [
        7654,
        7800
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The set of permissions that is displayed in the consent dialog are the same as what was selected in the Permissions to other applications control in the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        7801,
        7978
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "User consent experience",
      "pos": [
        7986,
        8009
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the user grants consent, an authorization code is returned to your application, which can be redeemed to acquire an access token and refresh token.",
      "pos": [
        8082,
        8235
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about this flow, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Web Application to Web API section<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-authentication-scenarios.md#web-application-to-web-api)</ept> section in <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Authentication Scenarios for Azure AD<ept id=\"p2\">](active-directory-authentication-scenarios.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8236,
        8489
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Accessing Web APIs in Other Applications",
      "pos": [
        8495,
        8535
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using the consent framework described above, you can configure your application to require permissions to access data exposed by web APIs in your directory.",
      "pos": [
        8537,
        8693
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, all applications can choose permissions from Azure Active Directory (Graph API) and Azure Service Management API, with the Azure AD “Enable sign on and read user’s profile” permission already selected by default.",
      "pos": [
        8694,
        8918
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your directory also has a subscription to Office 365, then web APIs and permissions for SharePoint and Exchange Online will also be available for selection.",
      "pos": [
        8919,
        9078
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can select from two types of permissions in the drop-down menus next to the desired web API:",
      "pos": [
        9079,
        9175
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Application Permissions: Your application needs to access the web API directly as itself (no user context).",
      "pos": [
        9179,
        9286
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This type of permission requires administrator consent and is also not available for native client applications.",
      "pos": [
        9287,
        9399
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Delegation Permissions: Your application needs to access the web API as the signed-in user, but with access limited by the selected permission.",
      "pos": [
        9403,
        9546
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This type of permission can be granted by a user unless the permission is configured as requiring administrator consent.",
      "pos": [
        9547,
        9667
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To add access to web APIs in other applications",
      "pos": [
        9674,
        9721
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign in to the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        9726,
        9765
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Click on the Active Directory icon on the left menu, then click on the desired directory.",
      "pos": [
        9770,
        9859
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the top menu, click Applications, and then click the application you want to configure.",
      "pos": [
        9864,
        9954
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Quick Start page will appear with single sign-on and other configuration information.",
      "pos": [
        9955,
        10044
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Expand the Access Web APIs in Other Applications section of the Quick Start, and then click the Configure it now link under the Select permissions section.",
      "pos": [
        10049,
        10204
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application properties page will appear.",
      "pos": [
        10205,
        10249
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Scroll down to the Permissions to other applications section.",
      "pos": [
        10254,
        10315
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The first column allows you to select from the available applications in your directory that expose a web API.",
      "pos": [
        10316,
        10426
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once selected, you may select application and delegation permissions that the web API exposes.",
      "pos": [
        10428,
        10522
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once selected, click the Save button on the command bar.",
      "pos": [
        10527,
        10583
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Clicking the Save button also automatically sets the permissions for your application in your directory based on the Permissions to other applications that you configured.",
      "pos": [
        10586,
        10770
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can view these application permissions by looking at the application Properties tab.",
      "pos": [
        10772,
        10860
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Exposing Web APIs to Other Applications",
      "pos": [
        10866,
        10905
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can develop a web API and make it available to other organizations by exposing your permission scopes to other application developers.",
      "pos": [
        10907,
        11045
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A correctly configured web API is made available just like the other Microsoft web APIs, including the Graph API and the Office 365 APIs.",
      "pos": [
        11046,
        11183
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your web API is made available by configuring an application manifest, which is a JSON file that represents your application’s identity configuration.",
      "pos": [
        11184,
        11334
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can expose your permission scopes by navigating to your application in the Azure Management Portal and clicking on the Application Manifest button on the command bar.",
