    },
    {
      "content": "This section describes how to update your application to access the Graph API, which is called “Azure Active Directory” in the list of Permissions to other applications.",
      "pos": [
        16370,
        16539
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It’s available by default for all applications that are registered with Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        16540,
        16621
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can select from the following permissions with the Graph API:",
      "pos": [
        16622,
        16687
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Permission name",
      "pos": [
        16690,
        16705
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Description",
      "pos": [
        16706,
        16717
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Type",
      "pos": [
        16718,
        16722
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Enable sign-on and read users' profiles",
      "pos": [
        16739,
        16778
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Allow users to sign in to the application with their organizational accounts and let the application read the profiles of signed-in users, such as their email address and contact information.",
      "pos": [
        16779,
        16970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Delegation permission only.",
      "pos": [
        16971,
        16998
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Can be consented by users.",
      "pos": [
        16999,
        17025
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Access your organization's directory",
      "pos": [
        17028,
        17064
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Allow the application to access your organization's directory on behalf of the signed-in user.",
      "pos": [
        17065,
        17159
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Delegation permission only.",
      "pos": [
        17160,
        17187
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Can be consented by users in a native client and only by an administrator for web applications.",
      "pos": [
        17188,
        17283
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Read directory data",
      "pos": [
        17286,
        17305
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Allow the application to read data in your organization's directory, such as users, groups and applications.",
      "pos": [
        17306,
        17414
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Delegation and application permission.",
      "pos": [
        17415,
        17453
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Must be consented by an administrator.",
      "pos": [
        17454,
        17492
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Read and write directory data",
      "pos": [
        17495,
        17524
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Allow the application to read and write data in your organization's directory, such as users and groups.",
      "pos": [
        17525,
        17629
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Delegation and application permission.",
      "pos": [
        17630,
        17668
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Must be consented by an administrator.",
      "pos": [
        17669,
        17707
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For existing users of the Azure Management Portal, setting the Read directory data and Read and write directory data application permissions through the new Permissions to other applications control is equivalent to the previous Manage Access wizard.",
      "pos": [
        17710,
        17960
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To see the permission scopes exposed by Office 365 please see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Authentication and Authorization using Common Consent Framework<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/office/office365/howto/common-app-authentication-tasks)</ept> topic.",
      "pos": [
        17962,
        18183
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Due to a current limitation, native client applications can only call into the Azure AD Graph API if they use the “Access your organization's directory” permission.",
      "pos": [
        18186,
        18363
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This restriction does not apply for web applications.",
      "pos": [
        18365,
        18418
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configuring Multi-Tenant Applications",
      "pos": [
        18424,
        18461
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When adding an application to Azure AD, you may want your application to be accessed only by users in your organization.",
      "pos": [
        18463,
        18583
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Alternatively, you may want your application to be accessed by users in external organizations.",
      "pos": [
        18584,
        18679
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These two application types are called single tenant and multi-tenant applications.",
      "pos": [
        18680,
        18763
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can modify the configuration of a single tenant application to make it a multi-tenant application, which this section discusses below.",
      "pos": [
        18764,
        18902
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It’s important to note the differences between a single tenant and multi-tenant application.",
      "pos": [
        18904,
        18996
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A single tenant application is intended for use in one organization.",
      "pos": [
        18997,
        19065
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They are typically a line-of-business (LoB) application written by an enterprise developer.",
      "pos": [
        19066,
        19157
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A single tenant application only needs to be accessed by users in one directory, and as a result, it only needs to be provisioned in one directory.",
      "pos": [
        19158,
        19305
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A multi-tenant application intended for use in many organizations.",
      "pos": [
        19306,
        19372
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They are typically a software-as-a-service (SaaS) application written by an independent software vendor (ISV).",
      "pos": [
        19373,
        19483
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-tenant applications need to be provisioned in each directory where they will be used, which requires user or administrator consent to register them.",
      "pos": [
        19484,
        19638
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Enabling External Users to Grant Access",
      "pos": [
        19645,
        19684
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are writing an application that you want to make available to your customers or partners outside of your organization, you will need to update the application definition in the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        19686,
        19894
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> When enabling external access, you must ensure that your application’s App ID URI belongs in a verified domain.",
      "pos": [
        19897,
        20021
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Additionally, the Return URL must begin with https://.",
      "pos": [
        20022,
        20076
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Application Objects and Service Principal Objects<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-application-objects.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        20077,
        20196
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To enable access to your app for external users",
      "pos": [
        20204,
        20251
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign in to the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        20256,
        20295
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Click on the Active Directory icon on the left menu, then click on the desired directory.",
      "pos": [
        20300,
        20389
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the top menu, click Applications, and then click the application you want to configure.",
      "pos": [
        20394,
        20484
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Quick Start page will appear with single sign-on and other configuration information.",
      "pos": [
        20485,
        20574
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Expand the Configure multi-tenant application section of the Quick Start, then click the Configure it now link in the Enable Access section.",
      "pos": [
        20579,
        20719
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application properties page will appear.",
      "pos": [
        20720,
        20764
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Click the Yes button next to Application is multi-tenant, then click the Save button on the command bar.",
      "pos": [
        20769,
        20873
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once you have made the change above, users and administrators in other organizations will be able to grant your application access to their directory and other data.",
      "pos": [
        20875,
        21040
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Granting Access Using the Consent Framework",
      "pos": [
        21046,
        21089
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To grant access using the consent framework, the client application must request authorization using OAuth 2.0.",
      "pos": [
        21091,
        21202
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Code samples<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/AzureADSamples)</ept> are available to show you how a web application, native application, or server/daemon application requests authorization codes and access tokens to call web APIs.",
      "pos": [
        21203,
        21415
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your web application may offer a sign-up experience for users.",
      "pos": [
        21417,
        21479
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you do offer a sign-up experience, it is expected that the user will click on a sign up (or sign-in button) that will redirect the browser to the Azure AD OAuth2.0 authorize endpoint or an OpenID Connect userinfo endpoint.",
      "pos": [
        21480,
        21705
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These endpoints allow the application to get information about the new user by inspecting the id_token.",
      "pos": [
        21706,
        21809
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Alternatively, your web application may also offer an experience that allows administrators to “sign up my company”.",
      "pos": [
        21811,
        21927
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This experience would also redirect the user to the Azure AD OAuth 2.0 authorize endpoint.",
      "pos": [
        21929,
        22019
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, you can also pass a prompt=admin_consent parameter to trigger the administrator consent experience, where the administrator will grant consent on behalf of their organization.",
      "pos": [
        22020,
        22209
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On successful consent, the response will contain admin_consent=true.",
      "pos": [
        22210,
        22278
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When redeeming an access token, you’ll also receive an id_token that will provide information on the organization and the administrator that signed up for your application.",
      "pos": [
        22279,
        22451
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Enabling OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant for Single Page Applications",
      "pos": [
        22458,
        22520
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single Page Application’s (SPAs) are typically structured with a JavaScript-heavy front end that runs in the browser, which calls the application’s web API back end to perform its business logic.",
      "pos": [
        22522,
        22717
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For SPAs hosted in Azure AD, you use OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant to authenticate the user with Azure AD and obtain a token that you can use to secure calls from the application's JavaScript client to its back end web API.",
      "pos": [
        22718,
        22936
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the user has granted consent, this same authentication protocol can be used to obtain tokens to secure calls between the client and other web API resources configured for the application.",
      "pos": [
        22937,
        23130
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant is disabled for applications.",
      "pos": [
        23131,
        23197
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can enable OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant for your application by setting the <ph id=\"ph1\">`oauth2AllowImplicitFlow`</ph>”` value in its application manifest, which is a JSON file that represents your application's identity configuration.",
      "pos": [
        23198,
        23416
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To enable OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant",
      "pos": [
        23424,
        23458
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign in to the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        23463,
        23502
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        23506,
        23599
      ],
      "content": "Click on the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Active Directory<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> icon on the left menu, then click on the desired directory."
    },
    {
      "content": "On the top menu, click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Applications<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and then click the application you want to configure.",
      "pos": [
        23603,
        23697
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Quick Start page will appear with single sign-on and other configuration information.",
      "pos": [
        23698,
        23787
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Click on the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Manage manifest<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button in the command bar, and select <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Download manifest<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        23791,
        23884
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Open the JSON application manifest file and set the “oauth2AllowImplicitFlow” value to “true”.",
      "pos": [
        23885,
        23979
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, it is “false”.",
      "pos": [
        23980,
        24006
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Save the updated JSON file and upload it by clicking the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Manage manifest<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button in the command bar, selecting <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Upload manifest<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, browsing to your updated manifest file and then selecting it.",
      "pos": [
        24052,
        24248
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once uploaded, your web API is now configured to use OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant to authenticate users.",
      "pos": [
        24249,
        24349
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Legacy Experiences for Granting Access",
      "pos": [
        24356,
        24394
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This section describes the legacy consent experience prior to March 12, 2014.",
      "pos": [
        24396,
        24473
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This experience is still supported, and is described below.",
      "pos": [
        24474,
        24533
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Prior to the new functionality, you could only grant the following permissions:",
      "pos": [
        24534,
        24613
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign on users from their organization",
      "pos": [
        24617,
        24654
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign on users and read the their organization’s directory data (as the application only)",
      "pos": [
        24658,
        24746
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign on users and read and write their organization’s directory data (as the application only)",
      "pos": [
        24750,
        24844
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can follow the steps in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Developing Multi-Tenant Web Applications with Azure AD<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn151789.aspx)</ept> to grant access for new applications registered in Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        24846,
        25051
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It’s important to note that the new consent framework allows much more powerful applications, and also enables users to consent to these applications instead of just administrators.",
      "pos": [
        25052,
        25233
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Building the Link that Grants Access for External Users (Legacy)",
      "pos": [
        25240,
        25304
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In order for external users to sign up for your app using their organizational accounts, you’ll need to update your app to show a button that links to the page on Azure AD that enables them to grant access.",
      "pos": [
        25306,
        25512
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Branding guidance for this sign up button is discussed in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Branding Guidelines for Integrated Applications<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-branding-guidelines.md)</ept> topic.",
      "pos": [
        25513,
        25672
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the user either grants or denies access, the Azure AD grant access page will redirect the browser back to your app with a response.",
      "pos": [
        25673,
        25810
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about application properties, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Application Objects and Service Principles<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-application-objects.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        25811,
        25952
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The grant access page is created by Azure AD, and you can find a link to it in your app’s Configuration page in the Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        25954,
        26088
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To get to the Configuration page, click on the Applications link in the top menu of your Azure AD tenant, click the app you want to configure, then click on Configure from the top menu of the Quick Start page.",
      "pos": [
        26089,
        26298
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The link for your application will look like this: <ph id=\"ph1\">`http://account.activedirectory.windowsazure.com/Consent.aspx?ClientID=058eb9b2-4f49-4850-9b78-469e3176e247&amp;RequestedPermissions=DirectoryReaders&amp;ConsentReturnURL=https%3A%2F%2Fadatum.com%2FExpenseReport.aspx%3FContextId%3D123456`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        26300,
        26582
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following table describes the parts of the link:",
      "pos": [
        26583,
        26635
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Parameter",
      "pos": [
        26638,
        26647
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Description",
      "pos": [
        26648,
        26659
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "ClientId",
      "pos": [
        26672,
        26680
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Required.",
      "pos": [
        26681,
        26690
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Client ID you obtained as part of adding your app.",
      "pos": [
        26691,
        26745
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "RequestedPermissions",
      "pos": [
        26748,
        26768
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Optional.",
      "pos": [
        26769,
        26778
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Access level that your app is requesting, that will be displayed to the user granting your app access.",
      "pos": [
        26779,
        26881
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If not specified, the requested access level will default to single sign-on only.",
      "pos": [
        26882,
        26963
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The other options are DirectoryReaders and DirectoryWriters.",
      "pos": [
        26964,
        27024
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See Application Access Levels for more details on these access levels.",
      "pos": [
        27025,
        27095
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "ConsentReturnUrl",
      "pos": [
        27098,
        27114
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Optional.",
      "pos": [
        27115,
        27124
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The URL that you want the grant access response returned to.",
      "pos": [
        27125,
        27185
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This value must be URL-encoded and must be under the same domain as the Reply URL configured in your app definition.",
      "pos": [
        27186,
        27302
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If not supplied, the grant access response will be redirected to your configured Reply URL.",
      "pos": [
        27303,
        27394
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Specifying a ConsentReturnUrl separate from the Reply URL will allow your app to implement separate logic that can process the response on a different URL from the Reply URL (which normally processes SAML tokens for sign on).",
      "pos": [
        27397,
        27622
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You may also specify additional parameters in the ConsentReturnURL encoded URL; these will be passed back as query string parameters to your app upon redirection.",
      "pos": [
        27623,
        27785
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This mechanism can be used to maintain additional info or to tie your app’s request for an access grant to the response from Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        27787,
        27921
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Grant Access User Experience and Response (Legacy)",
      "pos": [
        27928,
        27978
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When an application redirects to the grant access link, the following images demonstrate what the user will experience.",
      "pos": [
        27980,
        28099
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the user is not already signed in, they will be prompted to do so:",
      "pos": [
        28101,
        28170
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sign in to AAD",
      "pos": [
        28174,
        28188
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once the user is authenticated, Azure AD will redirect the user to the grant access page:",
      "pos": [
        28258,
        28347
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Grant Access",
      "pos": [
        28351,
        28363
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Only the company administrator of the external organization can grant access to your app.",
      "pos": [
        28434,
        28536
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the user is not a company administrator, they will be given the option to send mail to their company administrator to request that this app be granted access.",
      "pos": [
        28537,
        28698
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the customer has granted access for your app by clicking Grant Access, or if they have denied access by clicking Cancel, Azure AD sends a response to the ConsentReturnUrl or to your configured Reply URL.",
      "pos": [
        28700,
        28909
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This response contains the following parameters:",
      "pos": [
        28910,
        28958
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Parameter",
      "pos": [
        28961,
        28970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Description",
      "pos": [
        28971,
        28982
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "TenantId",
      "pos": [
        28995,
        29003
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The unique ID of the organization in Azure AD that has granted access for your app.",
      "pos": [
        29004,
        29087
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This parameter will only be specified if the customer granted access.",
      "pos": [
        29088,
        29157
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consent",
      "pos": [
        29160,
        29167
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The value will be set to Granted if the app was granted access, or Denied if the request was rejected.",
      "pos": [
        29168,
        29270
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Additional parameters will be returned to the app if they were specified as part of the ConsentReturnUrl encoded URL.",
      "pos": [
        29273,
        29390
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following is an example response to a grant access request that indicates the application has been authorized, and it includes a ContextID that was supplied in the grant access request: <ph id=\"ph1\">`https://adatum.com/ExpenseReport.aspx?ContextID=123456&amp;Consent=Granted&amp;TenantId=f03dcba3-d693-47ad-9983-011650e64134`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        29391,
        29700
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        29703,
        29831
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The access grant response will not contain a security token for the user; the app must sign the user in separately."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        29833,
